<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p>In 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="polymers-11-00861-f001">Figure 1</xref>a, the following notations are introduced: 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm1">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi mathvariant="bold">E</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>A</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>⋅</mo>
     <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>⋅</mo>
     <mi>exp</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>[</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mo>⋅</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">φ</mi>
        <mi>j</mi>
       </msub>
       <mrow>
        <mo>(</mo>
        <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
         <mi>r</mi>
        </mstyle>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
      <mo>]</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–the electric field vectors of the incident light beams; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm2">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>A</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm3">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">φ</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–spatial amplitude and phase profiles of recording beams, respectively; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm4">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>k</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mn>0</mn>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm5">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>k</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–wave vectors of the recording beams; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm6">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <msubsup>
        <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
         <mi>e</mi>
        </mstyle>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </msubsup>
       <mo>+</mo>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mo>⋅</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">ρ</mi>
        <mi>j</mi>
       </msub>
       <mo>⋅</mo>
       <msubsup>
        <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
         <mi>e</mi>
        </mstyle>
        <mi>j</mi>
        <mn>2</mn>
       </msubsup>
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
       <msqrt>
        <mrow>
         <mn>1</mn>
         <mo>+</mo>
         <msubsup>
          <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">ρ</mi>
          <mi>j</mi>
          <mn>2</mn>
         </msubsup>
        </mrow>
       </msqrt>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–unit complex polarization vectors in their own polarization bases; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm7">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
      <mn>1</mn>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>,
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm8">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mi>j</mi>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–orts of their own polarization bases; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm9">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mrow/>
      <mi>e</mi>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm10">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
       <mi>e</mi>
      </mstyle>
      <mrow/>
      <mi>o</mi>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–orts that determine the polarization of extraordinary and ordinary waves, respectively; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm11">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">ρ</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–ellipticity of polarization ellipses; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm12">
   <mrow>
    <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
     <mi>r</mi>
    </mstyle>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–radius-vector; 
 <italic>j</italic> = 0,1; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm13">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">θ</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mo> </mo>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">γ</mi>
      <mi>j</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–angles of incidence and polarization of the incident beams, respectively; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm14">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>E</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>E</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>r</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>t</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–vector of the electric field of the light wave in the sample; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm15">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">ψ</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–angle of rotation of the total light wave polarization; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm16">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">φ</mi>
      <mi>E</mi>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
        <mi>E</mi>
       </mstyle>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
        <mi>r</mi>
       </mstyle>
      </mrow>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>–angle of rotation of the director of LC molecules (droplets) 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm17">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>C</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>C</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal">
      <mi>r</mi>
     </mstyle>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>t</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> under the action of the photo-induced Freedericksz transition [
 <xref rid="B35-polymers-11-00861" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>,
 <xref rid="B36-polymers-11-00861" ref-type="bibr">36</xref>] in the 
 <italic>xOy</italic> plane.
</p>
